My Fathers Name was Aritippus, a Native of the City of Athens, a Senator of the higher Court, and of no mean Fortunes: It happen'd that my poor Mother having paid the Tribute that all humane Creatures owe to Nature, my Father reolved upon a econd Marriage, becaue he had as yet but one Son, and did not think him worthy of all his care; he therefore matched with a Woman, named Demoeneta, he was Fair enough, but had a Soul the mot black and fowl: She had no ooner entered our Houe, but he made her elf the abolute Mitres of it, and reduced all things to her Power and Pleaure; charming the

good man my Father with her Beauty, and officiouly oberving all his Humours: For he (if ever Woman) had the art to move the violence of Affection, and to make him paionately in love with her; if Affairs preed his departure, he wept; at his return he would meet him, accue the flownes of his coming, and protet he had perihed if he had tarryed never o little longer; at every word embracing him, and moitening her kies with her Tears, inomuch that my Father was o taken with her, as willingly he did ee or think of nothing ele. At firt he ued me as if I had been her own Son, and added this as a greater tye upon his Love; ometimes he would kis me, and deired that I might tay at home to play with her: This pleaed me, and not upecting what would follow, I admired that he expreed uch a Motherly Affection to me; but when he appeared more petulant, and that her kies grew more intemperate than became her, her carraige exceeding the bounds of modety; Then I began to upect, avoid, and repel her allurements; I omit the ret, becaue it would be tedious, to tell with what ways and promies he would entice me, how he would call me her weetet Favourite, her Heir, and oftentimes her Soul, making a mixture of fair Names, or any thing whereby he hoped I might be caught. In more erious and important matters bearing her elf as a Mother, but in dalliance hewing plainly he was in Love: At length this happened, upon the day of the great

olemnity, that we call the Panathineon, when the Athenians carry a Ship in proceion through the Streets in Honour of Minerva: Being then in the prime of my Youth; after I had ung the uual Hymn to the Goddes, the Rites ended, I returned home, yet veted in my Robe and Coronet; he had no ooner cat her Eyes upon me, but he lot her reaon, and could no longer diguie her paion, nor cover with her Art, the violence of her Flames, but running to me, embraced me, called me her young Hippolytus, her Theeus. Judge you in what cae I was then, that now bluh to peak it: That Evening my Father upped in the Prytaneum, and as is uual in thoe publick Feats and Meetings, tayed there all Night: Now when all our Houe were in their firt leep, he came to my Bod, and urged me to atisfie her unlawful deires; but I reiting both her Threats and Flatteries, fetching a deep igh, he left me, and that Night plotted revenge. My Father coming home about noon next day, and finding her a Bed, asked her how he did? She told him he was not well; but he preing her to peak particularly the caue of her uddain Sicknes;

As he was thus praying and conjuring, promiing me all his Etate for a Reward, one came from Charicles, and told me his Mater deired to peak with me; he is but over the way (he aid) in the Temple of Apollo, where he ings a Hymn to the God to appeae him, becaue he hath I know not how, been troubled in his Sleep to Night: I roe, and ending away Theagenes, made hate to the Temple, where I found Charicles itting in a Chair exceeding ad, and often ighing;

I demanded what Affliction made him o deolate? Alas, he replied, all this lat Night I have been troubled with fearful Dreams, and to make my Grief the greater, I hear my Daughter is till ick, and lain waking; and it afflicts me that her Sicknes falls in an unhappy time, becaue to Morrow is the Day prefixed, wherein the Prietes of Diana ought to give a Torch of Virgin-Wax to the Champions that run Armed, and to render them the Prize of the Victory; o that one of the two Evils mut necearily happen, that aiting at that Ceremony, her Malady will be augmented, or that her Abence will violate the Cutoms of the acred Games: therefore if this could not be done before, at leat apply ome Remedy unto her, and you hall do a mot charitable Office; which hall expres your Friendhip to me, and your Honour to the Gods: I know if you pleae, you can eaily uncharm her; for the Prophets of your Country can perform the greatet undertakings. I confeed I had been a little low, and putting it upon him as I had done upon Theagenes, I deired only the pace of a Day, and I would in that time compoe a Medicament hould heal her: But let us, aid I, now go to the Virgin, and conider her more attentively, and comfort her the bet that poible we can; and Charicles, it would be convenient you hould dicoure with her of me, and make me better known to her by your Commendations, that making me more familiar, and in greater eteem

with her, he may have the greater Faith in my Receipts. Be it o, he replied.

There words, Knemon, put her all into Confuion, and I aw clearly he delighted in them, yet was anxious and troubled how he might attain her hopes. In fine, aham'd to be brought thus to her Confeion, made her Cheeks die their Lilies red: And after he had a while tood mute; O Father, reply'd he, do you peak to me of marriage, and Counel me to take my own choice, as if my Father would conent, or that my Adverary wih'd it? For the young Gentleman (aid I) it is fixt; he is fater caught than you, in the ame tye, and I believe, at your firt interview, your Souls acknowledg'd the dignities and performances of one another, both burning in an equal Flame, which I have increas'd in him for young ake: But for him that is uppos'd to be your Father, he provides you another Husband, an acquaintance of yours, one Alcamenes: Let him provide (aid he) my Grave for Alcamenes, rather than my Bed for either; Theagenes hall marry me, or Death: but how do you know (I beeech you) that Charicles is but my uppoed Father: By this (aid I) and howed her the Mantle: Whence had you it, and how came you by it (he demanded of me) for after Charicles had received me in Aegypt from the hands of him that bred me, having brought me I know not how into this Country, he took it from me and kept it in a Box, to preerve it from being defaced or corrupted by the injury of time? How I got it (reply'd I) you

hall know hereafter, for the preent I pray you tell me if you have read the Incription: Confeing to me he did not know it; I declared to her her Parents, Country and Fortunes: To conclude, entreating me to tell heer the particulars, I read the whole dicoure to her, and did interpret it word by word: This bringing her to the knowledge of her elf, put greater pirit in her, and tranported her with a deire to ee her Parents; and asking me what was bet to be done; I began then to manifet my Counel to her, dicovering to her how all things went: I was once, Daughter, (aid I) in Aethiopia, carried thither with a deire to gain their Widom; I was there made known to your Mother Perina, for that Court entertaineth Learned Men, with all Humanity, and there was a great opinion of me, for as much as I had joyned the Widom of the Aegyptians, with that of the Aethiopian Sages, which is made of great authority in that Nation. But your Mother when he aw I prepar'd for my departure home, recounted to me all your Fortune: Having firt obliged me to ecreie by oath, and telling me he durt not dicover it to her own Priets: She prayed me to demand of the Gods, if you were preferv'd, and in what part of the World you lived, foramuch as he could not undertand there was any uch in all Aethiopia, though he had made curious enquiry: But the Gods having revealed all to me, I told her you were alive, and where;

he then entreated me to eek you out, and bring you back into your Country, in regard that ince your birth the brief he conceived for you had hindered conception in her; and that he was now ready, if you could be found, to confes all that had happen'd to your Father, perwading herelf that the long time they had lived together, had ufficiently confirmed him in her Faith by true proof; and that he would be extremely taken with unexpected joy, to leave his Scepter in the hands of his own Child. This the Queen aid to me, conjuring me by my Vow to her, wherein I had called the Sun to witnes, an Oath it is not lawful for our Priets to violate.

Being now come to the ide of the Lake and about to take Water, they perceiv'd a Troop of Armed Men paing over to the Iland, a ight that o troubled them, as they remain'd a great while lot in atonihment, as if the Injuries of Fortune raged inceantly upon them. At length the Souldiers being almot arriv'd, Chariclea aid, it was bet to fly and return to the Cave and there to conceal themelves; and as he pake he fled, but the tay of Theagenes detained her: How long, aid he, hall we fly our Fate, that every where purues us? No, no, let us yield to Fortune, and not oppoe our elves to her violence that breaks in upon us; what

hall we gain by it, but vain errour and a wandring Life, and to be inulted over by new miery from time to time? Alas, do you not ee how to our banihment Fortune hath added the Robberies of Pirates, ingag'd us in all the dangers of the Sea, and contended with great indutry, to make us more mierable by Land? hath he not expos'd us to the danger of War? ubmitted us to the mercy of Thieves? A while ince we were prioners ubject to the pleaure of another; then we were left alone depriv'd of all company; then he made a how to give us our Liberty; and now he ends thee Murderers to make an end of all; in uch a War he plays againt us, making us her Scene of Mirth, her Comedy, or rather Tragedy. But why do I not then abbreviate this Lamentable Hitory of our Loves, and deliver our elves into the Hands of our Murderers, leat if he tudy to make the end of her play inufferable, we be forced with our own hands to kill our elves? Chariclea conented to one part of what Theagenes aid, but not to all; telling him he had great reaon to complain of the cruelty of fortune; but for all that, it were not well advied to yield themelves voluntarily to their Enemies, being they were not ure thoe Men would kill them, when they had them in their power: Neither was it likely they had o gentle a detiny as would grant them a peedy death, and free them from their calamities; but it might be, they hould be reerved for Slaves;

and what Death, aid he, can be o cruel as the condition of uch a Life, to be expoed to the fatal indignities of barbarous and wicked Villains? which let us decline by all means, and to our uttermot power, meauring hope and ucces by the experiment of our paed accidents, ince we have often, and now lately, ecaped alive, more incredibly as from greater dangers.
